{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00222254632/1930082601/0612.xml":{"full_text":"20\nI tridirS; oSB\niim ir\nSerious Decline Is Not Anticipated By Spectator, Viewing Market Outlook\n1 9 _ _..\nBUSBIESSIMPHOVEMENT\nTO All MART TREND\nAggressive Operations for Rise to Be Halted\nBy Three-Day Holiday; Buying of Good\nStocks on Lows Advised\nty THE SPECTATOR\nThe market broke out of its dilly-dallying yesterday by\nturning downward.\nVanadium upset\u2019 the bandwagon by breaking sharply on\nunfavorable July earnings estimates. The oils added an addi\ntional sour note, giving way to further pressure.\nIt. was noticeable, however, that leaders like Steel and Can\nwere very stubborn and retreated grudgingly. This is encourag\ning. and if the,pivotal stocks act this way again today I think\nthe reaction will be short lived.\nI do not anticipate a serious decline in any event. Business\nis beginning to look up and the coming of fall will undoubtedly\nput a little pep into things. Stocks have already discounted\na good deal of improvement by their recent advance but they\ncan still work higher,. I belieye.\nThere is a three-day holiday at the end of the week, which\nwill halt aggressive operations for the rise. At that the better\nstocks appear to be a buy on further weakness on the likelihood\nthey will sell higher after -Labor Day.\n-A Bullish Note\nThe financial community gen\nerally seems to have overlooked\nthe fact that the backlog of\nUnited States Steel at the end\nof last month was only little be\nlow the same period last year,\nyet steel\u2019s operating rate now\nis only about 62 per cent of\ncapacity, against over 90 per\ncent then.\nThis is very significant. Steel\n.eould easily step up operations\nto TO and even 75 per cent of\ncapacity without abandoning its\nultra-conservative policy. Well\ninformed interests expect this\naction very soon. Steel obviously\nhas been a different stock this\npast week than in a long time.\nIt has shown a lot of fight on\nthe tape and has been the spear\nhead of every advance. I con\nsider steel one of the best buys\non the list on any further weak\nness.\nInsiders and rich investors have\nbeen picking up American Radia\ntor for some time, I am told.\nThe stock has moved in a nar\nrow range since its break in\nJune. Earnings for the first six\nmonths were poor, but the divi\ndend will very likely be paid.\nThe company is in a strong\nfinancial position and will bene\nfit from any upswing in the\nbuilding industry.\nVanadium\nVanadium certainly looked sick\nyesterday, closing off more than\n6 points on the report that it\nhad operated at a loss in July.\nI told my readers some time ago\nto stay away from the stock, de\nclaring then that \u25a0it was selling\ntoo high on profits from actual\noperations and that well-informed\ninterests considered its prospects\nexaggerated.\nVanadium is just one of those\nfine speculative mediums for\nprofessionals and day-to-day\ntraders. It is too dangerous foi\nthe man on the street. It may\ndevelop sensational earning power\ncome day, but there seems to be\nno reason for anticipating any\nthing of the sort until the com\npany can actually, show some\nthing.\nI am told that fixed trusts\nhave been heavy buyers of stocks\nin the last two weeks. There has\nalso been considerable scale buy\ning in the high-grade dividend\npaying issues. In general, the\nstreet is agreed that the buying\nof l/.te has been better than the\nselling except in individual weak\nspots.\nChicago Stocks\nTraded Higher\nCHICAGO. Aug. 26.\u2014The fifty\nmost active stocks traded on the\n-Chicago Stock Exchange during\nthe week ended August 23 had a\nmarket value* of $2,579,342,068 at\nthe close of business Saturday, as\ncompared with $2,561,939,635 at\nthe close of the previous week,\naccording to a compilation by Otis\nCo. This represents an in\ncrease so $17,402,433 or .68 per\ncent.\nOtis Co.\u2019s analysis shows that\n34 of these stocks were listed avd\ntraded in last year. These stocks\nhad a market value of $1,568,741,-\n001 Saturday as compared with\n$2,604 668.614 on August 24, 1929;\na decrease of $1,035,927.61-3 or\n39.77 per cent.\nYour\nAttention\nIs Directed\nto the Busi\nness Service An\nnouncem e nts\nfeatured in -to\nday\u2019s\u2014\nTimet Classified Ads\nWASHINGTON TINESfefHtINCIAL NEWS\nA Sound Stock\nInterests bullish on Liggett\nand Myers assert that it is\nselling out of line. They point\nout that earnings on the stock\nthis year will be about that on\nthe American Tobacco new issues,\napproximately $8.50 a share; that\nthe dividend rate is about the\nsame, yet Liggett and Myers is\nselling at a discount of more\nthan 26 points.\nOs course, American Tobacco\nis setting the pace for the to\nbacco companies in sales and\nearnings this year. Liggett and\nMyers, however, has excellent\nmanagement and a high invest\nment rating. I believe it\u2019s a good\nbuy around current levels. It\nhas been acting much better\nmarket-wise in the last week.\nAmerican Telephone is one of\nthe best on the big board. Around\ncurrent levels it is only slightly\nmore than 10 points above its\nlow for the year and over 60\npoints below its high. It has\nbeen well bought for some time.\nThere won\u2019t be any ride in the\nmarket without a corresponding\nadvance in telephone, which gives\nthe stock both safety and specu\nlative appeal.\nHere and-There\nForeign Power and National\nPower were among the few stocks\nthat closed with net gains yes\nterday. Both are being tipped\nfor shaii> rides.\nInterests close to National Dis\ntillers are bullish on the long\nterm prospects. Much is expected\nfrom the company\u2019s new process\nfor making cheap butanol.\nBohn Aluminum and Brass is\nselling at a price that speaks\ndanger for its $3 dividend. Earn\nings were off sharply this year.\nThere has been some scale buy\ning for a long pull. The com\npany is in line to benefit from\nany improvement in the auto\nmobile and aviation industries,\nits chief customers.\nOne wit says the Petroleum\nstocks should spread a little of\ntheir own oil on their troubled\nwaters.\nUnited,. Aircraft at. its high\nyesterday was said to have been\nwithin a point of the pool\u2019s ob\njective.\nThere is a strong crowd work\ning in Lorillard, I am told. It\nwill move with the Tobaccos.\nUnited States Pipe and Foundry\nacts as it it were being groomed\nfor a play. It was mentioned\nhere a couple of points lower.\nOffer United Ohio\nUtilities Preferred\nA new issue of $1,350,000 6 per\ncent prior preference stock of the\nUnited Ohio Utilities Company,\ncontrolled indirectly by the\nUnited Light Power Co., is*\nbeing offered today by Otis Co.\nat 98% per share and accrued\ndividends, to yield 6.09 per cent.\nProceeds of this issue will be\nused for the retirement of $1,262,-\n800 par value of the company\u2019s 7\nper cent prior preference stock.\nThe company was incorporated in\n1926 and owns all the common\nstock of the Southern Ohio Elec\ntric Company.\nW. B. HIBBS CO.\nThe ONLY New York Stock Exchange House\nHaving Its Main Office in Washington\nNexv York Stock Exchange\nBoston Stock Exchange\nPhiladelphia Stock Exchange\nWashington Stock Exchange\nNew York Cotton Exchange\nChicago Board of Trade\nAmerican Bankers Association\nDistrict Bankers Association\nI\nHIBBS BUILDING\nNational 0540 WASHINGTON, D. C.\nTHE WASHINGTON \u2022TIMES\nj Vacation j\nJ\n\u2014Times Staff Photo\nLAURENCE A. SLAUGHTER\nVICE PRESIDENT of the\nCommercial National Bank,\nwho is on vacation at Upper\nSaranac, N. Y.\nHlfflWS\nME REPORTED\nFire and marine insurance com\npanies authorized to do business\nin New York State had assets as\nof December 31, 1929, amounting\nto $2,880,648,913, an increase of\n$226,152,701 over the year 1928.\nThis is revealed by Thomas F.\nBehan, acting superintendent of\ninsurance, in a report which cov\ners the aggregate business of 318\njoint-stock and 74 mutual fire\nand marine companies.\nCombined capital of the com\npanies totaled $411,202,278. repre\nsenting an increase of $62,638,258\nover last year, while surplus\ngained $121,035,091, totaling\n$1.M4,056.586.\nFire risks written during the\nyear alone were $186,776,604,563,\nwhile other risks written amounted\nto $199,660,502,966, a gain of\n$19,390,444,120 and $25,556,303,-\n702, respectively.\nTotal income last year was\n$1,423,271,154. a gain of no less\nthan $87,293,240, while income on\nfire premiums aggregated $793,-\n053.305. $23,188,641 ahead of the\npreceding year.\nL, I. National Rank\nPlans Stock Split\nShareholders of the Long\nIsland National Bank, Astoria,\nLong Island, will hold their an\nnual meeting at the bank\u2019s head\nquarters on Tuesday afternoon\nIn addition to the regular busi\nness they will consider and vote\nupon the board\u2019s proposal to re\nduce the par value of the bank\u2019s\nshares from SIOO to $lO and to\nsplit the present setup of 2,500\nshares on the basis of 10 of the\nnew issue for each old share held.\nA capital increase of from $250,-\n000 to $400,000, which will be\nrepresented by an issuance of\n13.000 additional shares, will also\nbe considered by the shareholders.\nRepublic to Spend\n$1,500,000 on Plant\nThe Republic Steel Corporation\ntoday announced the completion\nof plan for the expansion and\nimprovement involvim the expen\nditure of $x,500.000. On Septem\nber 1 the company\u2019s blast furnace\nwill extinguished and improve\nment made on it that will in\ncrease its ipacity from 700 tons\nto 1,000 tons.\nFord Reopens\nMemphis Plant\nRICHMOND, Aug. 26.\u2014Ford\nMotor Company plant at Mem\nphis. Tenn., has resumed opera\ntions with employment of 1,200\nmen. Production schedule calls\nfor daily output of around 150\nunits. y\nVAST PROPERTY\nSDLDHEREBY\nWARDMAN\nInterest in $30,000,000 Hotel\nAnd Apartments Is Taken\nOver by Operating Concern\nHarry Wardman, prominent real\nestate operator, last night an\nnounced his retirement from in\nterests in hotel and apartment\nhouse properties valued at more\nthan $30,000,000 in the Capital.\nThe properties passed into the\nhands of the Hotels Management\nand Securities Corporation, which\nhas been identified with Wardman\ninterests here for the last year.\nThe properties include the\nWardman Park. Carlton. Roose\nvelt, Annapolis and Chastleton ho\ntels and a number of apartment\nbuildings with a total of more\nthan 7,000 rooms.\nNo Cash Involved\nWardman explained that no\ncash was involved in the transac\ntion. which would include no\nfinancial consideration. He also\nstated that the passing of the\nproperities to other interests\nwould mark his retirement from\nthe hotel and apartment field,\nbut declared his intention of con\ntinuing activities strictly in a\nreal estate line.\nJ. Reed Lane, of Davenport;\nlowa, president of the new con\ntrolling corporation, declared that\nmore than $200,000 had been\nappropriated for improvement of\nthe properties. Other executive\nofficers of the corporation are\nEmory L. Coblentz, of Frederick.\nMd., chairman of the board;\nGeorge E. Allen, of Chicago; F.\nRoger Miller, of Ashville, N. C..\nand Alfred C. Torgeson, of New\nv ork, vice presidents.\nThe corporation also owns a\nresort hotel at Ashville and has\ninterests in T cwa, Minnesota and\nNew York.\nWardman Long a Leader\nThe new owners assume full\ncontrol and management of the\nWardman Realty and Construc\ntion Company, and its subsidiary.\nWardman Real Estate Properies,\nInc., Wardman\u2019s associates in\nthese enterprises also sever their\nconnections.\nFor more than 20 years. Ward\nman has been one of the Capital\u2019s\nbiggest real estate operators and\nbegan building on a large scale\nduring the World War. He first\nconstructed apartment buildings\nand stores and then began erec\ntion of large hotels and hotel\napartments.\nVote Extra Welch\nGrape Co, Dividend\nWelsh Grape Juice Company\ndirectors declared an extra divi\ndend of 25 cents and the regular\nquarterly dividend of 25 cents a\nshare on the common stock and\nthe regular quarterly dividend of\n$1.75 on the preferred stock.\nAll dividends are payable Au\ngust 30 to stock of record August\n15.\nCocoa Futures Sell\nAt New Low Levels\nEvidence of plentiful offerings\nof cocoa in the open market, de\nspite the fact that the British\ncombine has accumulated most\nof the world's visible supplies, re\nsulted in extensive liquidation on\nthe Cocoa Exchange during the\npast week, with prices establish\ning new low records.\nNehi Sales Show\n25% July Increase\nSales of the Nehi Corporation,\nmanufacturers of carbonated bev\nerages, were adversely affected in\nthe first half of the current year\nby the late arrival of the hot\nweather period, but sales in July\nwere in turn benefited by a 25\nper cent, increase, according to\nC. A. Hatcher, president.\nReal Estate\nLoans\n(D. C. Pronerty Only)\n6%\nNo Commission Charged\nYou can take 12 years to pay off\nyour loan without the expense of\nrenewing. SI,OOO for $lO per\nmonth including interest and\nprincipal. Larger or smaller\nloans at proportionate rates.\nPERPETUAL\nBUILDING\nASSOCIATION\nEstablished 1881\nLargest in Washington\nAsset* Over $23,000,000\nCor 11th and E W. W.\nJAMES BERRT. President\nEDWIRn C. BALTS. Seeretarr\nTA\u00ab National Daily\nLOCAL STOCKS\n(Furnished by W B Hibbs 4 Co.I 4\nSALES\nWashington Railway Electric\n4s, SI,OOO 89%.\nCapital Traction Co., 10 61;\n10 61; 48 61; 1 61; 10\n61%.\nAPTER CALL\nPotomac Electric 6s, \u201953, SI,OOO\n108%.\nPotomac Electric cons ss, SI,OOO\n102%.\nWashington Railway <fc Electric\n4s, SI,OOO 89%.\nWashington Gas 6s \u201cA,\u201d SI,OOO\n102%.\nCapital Traction Co., 10\n61%.\nPublic ~ftilltv Bonds I I\nAmer Tei 4 Tel 4 1101 I\nAmer Tel Tel 4%\u00bb 1101 1.....\nAm T 4 T Ctl Tr s*. 1105% 1....\nAnacostla 4 Pot R R 6b. ..1 82%l\nAna th Pot Guar 5b .....I 91\nC 4 P Tel ot Va 5s |1()2%I\nCep Traction R R 5s j 93 I 94\nCity 4 Suburban Jb ..I 81) 83\nGeorgetown Gee let 5s 1101%;\nPotomac Elec Cons 5s T02%1103%\nPotomac Elec 6s 110 S I\nWash Alex 4 Mt V ctf....l 6 I\nWash Balto 4 An 5s I 50 I 60\nWashington Gas 5a 1103% 1104%\nWash Gas 6s series A....1103 1103%\nWash Gas 6a series B 1105 IlO<%\nWash Ry 4 Elec htt. 89% 90\nMiscellaneous Bonds _|_\nBarber 4 Ross Inc 6%t....| 89 \u2018I 90\nChevy Chase Club 5%b 1100 I\nD. C. Paper Mtir jSO 75\nW M. Cold Storage 5s 1 95 I\nWash Cons Title 6s 90 |loo\nPublic Utility Stocks I\nAmer Tel 4 Tel 1212*\nCapitol Traction Co 61 62\nWash Gas Lt Co 1121 11.10\nX 4 W Steamboat |240\n\u2022Pot Elec Power \u00abs pM |llO 111\n\u2022Pot Elec Pwr 5%a pfd... |IOB |10\u00bb\nWash Ry 4 El com !500 I\n\u2666Wash Ry th El Pfd 98%|100\nNational Bunk Ktoeka I\nCa pll al 1230 250\nColumbia 439\nCommercial (stamped).... 12'5 -.40\nV i \"J ricf l 2 2 '2s\u00ae\nr ederal-American 1275 'ftoo\nLiberty (200 1220\nLincoln 1400 440\nMetropolitan |350 4O\nBiggs |47* 525\no' u*? 76 1316\nashington 1246 1\u201965\nTrust lomiisnr Stocks i *1\nAmer Sec 4 Tr ~*Co 3g& *4oT\nFashion has Grown up\nShe\u2019s a Lady now!\nZ\nREMEMBER the period of ruffles and\ngirlish sashes the square cut dresses of the\n\u201cawkward age?\u201d Then came the long tube figure R 5%\nthe boyish \u201cyoung thing\u201d with daringly it\nshort skirts and on her heels the frilly V i\nwoman of 1929\nBut have you met that NEW WOMAN? That yjb\nfall 1930 person who has a new clothes charm? I\nThe daily articles, \u201cWhat\u2019s In Fashion?\u201d tells\nyou what she wears and HOW.\nAU\n/V \u00abn P\u00abjwl\n/A A I T\nJ I I IH\nI l I ri\\ M nrjMIH\nu/ if/ i I \\Ji| ILF JyjHMBBMM\n\nr\nRead \u201cWhat\u2019s in Fashion?\u201d\nf\nDirected by Amos Parrish\nExclusively in the Washington Times\nTUESDAY, AUGUST 26, 1930\nIBM Ask\nMarch Bk 4 Tr 125 lI6U\nContinental Trust 120 1140\nN'at'l Bav 4 Tr 545 600\nTrust 260* 1300\nWash Loan 4 Tr |4\u00ab& 510\nSavings Bank Stocks I I\nBank of Bethesda I 59 65\nCommerce 4 Savings J 330\nEast Washington I 26 35\nPotomac Savings Bank |65 75\nSec Sav 4 Coml Bk (471 1600\nSeventh Street,., 1316\nUnited States |530 1630\nWssh Mechanics 50\nFire Insurance Stocks I\nAmerican ...|320\nCorcoran ......1150 1.....\nFiremen's 32 I 38\nNational Uihon .....|22 j 26\nTitle insurance Stocks I I\nColumbia J 8% I 12\nI Real Estate 1165 1175\nTitle 4 Inv Co Md c0m...,l 20 I 30\nMlacellaneoaa Stocks J\nBarber 4 Ross Inc C0m....| 15 It\n\u2022Chevy Chase Dairy pfd....1102 109\nCol Sand 4 Grav pfd I 90 I 94\nMedical Bldg C0rp....1100 L...\nDW? Paper Mfg pfd I 70\nDistrict Nstlonal Sec pfd.. I 70 85\nEmer Bromo-Selz \u201cA\u201d 30 32\nFederal Storage pfd 110 125\nFed-Amer Co c0mm........ 31 33\nFed-Amer Co pfd 99 |lOl\nMansion Monotvpe 114 118%\nMer Tr 4 Stge com 103 110\nMer Tr th Stge pfd 95%T00\nMergentha ler Lino 96 197 V.\nNatl Mtvc 4 Inv nfd 5 5%\nPeoples Drug S pfd |102%|105\nIleal Eat. M 4 G pfd I 6U\nSecurity Storage. 1112 1114\nTer Ref 4 Wh Corp I 47 I 52\nThe Carpel Corp... I 23 I 24\nW Meeh Mtge com I 8%l\nWash Med Bldg Corp I 95 1.....\nWoodward 4 Lothrop pfd., 107 T1 2\n\u2022Ed. dividends\nOUTPUT DECREASES\n1\nThe power output of the elec\ntric subsidiaries of the American\nWater Works and Electric Com-\npany for the month of July\ntotaled 150,039,797 kilowatt hours,\na decrease of 5 per cent over the\noutput of 157,902,254 kilowatt\nhours for the corresponding\nmonth of 1929.\nFor the seven months ended\nJuly 31, 1930, power output\ntotaled 1,109,481,005 kilowatt\nhours\nBAND ROW ENDS\nON NEW PL!N\nThe crisis of the bond tangle\nat Police Court appeared past to\nday, following thhe issuance of an\norder Saturday night by Major\nHenry G. Pratt, superintendent\nof police, for police to place only\none charge against a man at the\ntime of arrest.\nThis will result in a lower bond\nthan has been the case when\nseveral charges were placed\nagainst nearly every suspect\narrested.\nThe action of the chief of\npolice followed a long discussion\nwhich began last Monday with\nthe refusal of Prosecutor Hart to\nmake out papers on 13 alleged\nrum cases, because of warrantless\nraids or lack of evidence. At\nthat time Hart suggested lower\nbonds, to which Major Pratt re\ni plied that the police had nothing\nto do with setting bonds. Hart\ndeclared, however, that should\nthe police discontinue the practice\nof placing numerous unsupport\nable charges against persons\narrested, the bonds would auto\nmatically be less.\nThe discussion finallly led to\nthe rumor of collusion between\nthe police and professional bonds\nmen. This has caused Milton\nKronheim. president of the Pro\nfessional Bondsmen\u2019s Association,\nto announce that he will ask\nUnited States Attorney Leo A.\nRover for an investigation of\nthe matter.\nHart declared Saturday that\npolice co-operated 100 per cent\nin his effort to book \u201cfewer but\nbetter cases.\u201d After Monday,\nfewer cases came in, and all but\ncne \u201cheld water\u201d out of the total\nfor the remainder of the week.\nRAILROAD ADOS\nEOUIPMENT\nCHICAGO, Aug. 25.\u2014The ne\ncessity of preparing now for fu\nture improvement in business is\nemphasized in a statement made\ntoday by V. V. Boatner. president\nof the Chicago Great Western\nrailroad. The Great Western,\naccording to its president, is con\ntinuing on its aggressive 1930\nprogram of improvement despite\nthe general reduction in traffic\nvolume and revenues which has\nhit all railroads. Large equip\nment purchases, increased main\ntenance work, and steps to im\nprove the operating efficiency\nand economy of the road have\nbeen vigorously prosecuted since\nthe first of the year.\nBoatner said:\n\u201cOur attitude is best evi\ndenced by the fact that we\nhave just ordered 15 new heavy\nfreight locomotives for delivery\nin November. This order was\na duplicate of one filled earlier\nthis year, and will give the\nGreat Western 30 of the latest\ntype locomotives, capable of\nhandling a substantially addi\ntional volume of traffic. We\nexpect to not only improve\nservice, but effect additional\neconomies through the opera\ntion of this new power equip\nment.\n\u201cMaintenance and improve\nment work has been conducted\non an increased scale since the\nfirst of the year. While the\nGreat Western has suffered\nfrom smaller revenues along\nwith other railroads, we have\nthe utmost confidence in a\nreturn of prosperity and the\nfurther development of the\nterritory we serve.","height":"30480","width":"24217"}}
